"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The np.sinc function returns an array of sinc values, but the sinc function is defined as sinc(x) = sin(pi*x)/(pi*x) if x != 0, and sinc(0) = 1. When x is an integer other than 0, the sinc function will return 0 due to the sin(pi*x) term being 0. However, when the input to np.sinc is an integer array, the sinc values are computed at those integer points. The sinc function is not defined at x = 0 in the classical sense but numpy defines np.sinc(0) as 1. But np.sinc will still return values close to but not exactly 0 for other integer inputs due to floating point precision. Therefore, comparing sinc_result[1] to 0 using the equality operator will likely fail.\",\n  \"patch\": \"7,8c7,8\\n< assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n< assert sinc_result[1] == 0, \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\\n---\\n> np.testing.assert_allclose(sinc_result[0], 1)\\n> np.testing.assert_allclose(sinc_result[1:], 0)\"\n}"